00:32:33.287 --> 00:32:34.370
JOHN DOLHUN: Forest fires.

00:32:34.370 --> 00:32:36.830
That would definitely be
a big source of mercury.

00:32:36.830 --> 00:32:38.860
Yeah.

00:32:38.860 --> 00:32:39.790
Anything else?

00:32:44.260 --> 00:32:45.392
Yeah, Ryan?

00:32:45.392 --> 00:32:47.350
AUDIENCE: I mean, it's
definitely in the water,

00:32:47.350 --> 00:32:50.920
but like for [INAUDIBLE]

00:32:50.920 --> 00:32:51.720
JOHN DOLHUN: Yeah.

00:32:51.720 --> 00:32:52.140
Yeah.

00:32:52.140 --> 00:32:52.640
Oh, yeah.

00:32:52.640 --> 00:32:55.920
It's in the dirt and
rocks and evaporating out.

00:32:55.920 --> 00:32:56.880
Yeah.

00:32:56.880 --> 00:33:02.100
I mean, another big source would
be volcanoes-- natural source.

00:33:02.100 --> 00:33:02.670
Yeah.

00:33:02.670 --> 00:33:07.260
So probably about 2/3 of it
comes from our fossil fuels

00:33:07.260 --> 00:33:09.960
and a third of it comes
from natural sources.

00:33:09.960 --> 00:33:13.020
But once it gets
up there, once it's

00:33:13.020 --> 00:33:16.350
in the atmosphere, this
elemental mercury--

00:33:16.350 --> 00:33:19.740
there are plenty of things
up there that can oxidize it.

00:33:19.740 --> 00:33:21.540
There's ozone up there.

00:33:21.540 --> 00:33:24.090
There's hydroxide radicals.

00:33:24.090 --> 00:33:27.700
There's chlorine and
bromine in the troposphere.

00:33:27.700 --> 00:33:33.290
So this elemental mercury
gets oxidized to mercury 2.

00:33:33.290 --> 00:33:35.270
And then it rains outside.

00:33:35.270 --> 00:33:36.200
Right?

00:33:36.200 --> 00:33:39.410
Where do you think that
mercury 2 goes when it rains?

00:33:39.410 --> 00:33:40.800
It's coming down on us.

00:33:40.800 --> 00:33:41.300
Right?

00:33:41.300 --> 00:33:43.430
It's going into the water.

00:33:43.430 --> 00:33:46.190
And once it gets
in the water there

00:33:46.190 --> 00:33:48.120
are a couple of things
that can happen.

00:33:48.120 --> 00:33:51.530
It can have it can
be photoreduced here.

00:33:51.530 --> 00:33:54.680
And you can form the
elemental mercury back.

00:33:54.680 --> 00:33:59.870
And some of that can vaporize
back up into the atmosphere.

00:33:59.870 --> 00:34:02.330
Or the mercury too
can get down here

00:34:02.330 --> 00:34:04.630
into the depths of the water.

00:34:04.630 --> 00:34:08.330
And this is where the
bad things happen.

00:34:08.330 --> 00:34:12.380
This is where the nasty
methyl mercury is formed.

00:34:12.380 --> 00:34:16.810
So once it gets down here we
know that mercury loves sulfur.

00:34:16.810 --> 00:34:20.199
So it can attach
itself to this--

00:34:20.199 --> 00:34:23.230
there's plenty of hydrogen
sulfide in the water.

00:34:23.230 --> 00:34:26.469
It can attach itself to
the sulfur and form mercury

00:34:26.469 --> 00:34:28.480
sulfide.

00:34:28.480 --> 00:34:33.219
And this is a neutral molecule.

00:34:33.219 --> 00:34:35.290
Being a neutral
molecule it can go right

00:34:35.290 --> 00:34:38.150
through a bacterial cell wall.

00:34:38.150 --> 00:34:41.300
And once it's inside
of a bacteria--

00:34:41.300 --> 00:34:42.909
there are some
bacteria down there

00:34:42.909 --> 00:34:45.370
that produce methyl mercury.

00:34:45.370 --> 00:34:48.560
Nobody knows how it's done.

00:34:48.560 --> 00:34:52.210
They know that the
mercury sulfide goes in,

00:34:52.210 --> 00:34:55.040
but they don't know
the exact mechanism.

00:34:55.040 --> 00:34:56.710
The other thing
that's not known is

00:34:56.710 --> 00:34:59.050
that there are some
fish out there that

00:34:59.050 --> 00:35:05.980
have millions of parts of
mercury in their systems,

00:35:05.980 --> 00:35:08.860
much more than the
surrounding water.

00:35:08.860 --> 00:35:11.800
So there's got to be some
other sources of this methyl

00:35:11.800 --> 00:35:15.130
mercury down there somewhere
that they haven't really

00:35:15.130 --> 00:35:17.080
pinpointed.

00:35:17.080 --> 00:35:20.350
So once we get this
methyl mercury--

00:35:20.350 --> 00:35:22.810
I just told you it loves sulfur.

00:35:22.810 --> 00:35:24.100
Right?

00:35:24.100 --> 00:35:26.480
So you get this
stuff in the body--

00:35:26.480 --> 00:35:29.020
this organic form of mercury.

00:35:29.020 --> 00:35:33.910
It's going to go for your
cysteine amino acids.

00:35:33.910 --> 00:35:38.530
And it forms a covalent
bond to the sulfur.

00:35:38.530 --> 00:35:45.990
So you've got this carboxy ethyl
sulfonyl methyl mercury here.

00:35:45.990 --> 00:35:50.640
Now you think about the
cysteine amino acids--

00:35:50.640 --> 00:35:53.110
we've got them in our proteins.

00:35:53.110 --> 00:35:56.430
So this methyl mercury,
once it's inside of ourself

00:35:56.430 --> 00:36:02.730
it can go for all the proteins
and infiltrate covalently bond

00:36:02.730 --> 00:36:06.710
and hook up to all
these cysteines.

00:36:06.710 --> 00:36:08.900
Once we get methyl
mercury inside of us

00:36:08.900 --> 00:36:16.040
from eating the fish,
it's like bioaccumulation.

00:36:16.040 --> 00:36:17.630
It's down the biofood chain.

00:36:17.630 --> 00:36:21.080
It starts with the plankton,
then the small fish,

00:36:21.080 --> 00:36:22.800
and the bigger fish.

00:36:22.800 --> 00:36:24.980
Then we get it.

00:36:24.980 --> 00:36:28.010
This stuff-- 90% of
the methyl mercury

00:36:28.010 --> 00:36:33.610
can actually come out of our
gut, get into our bloodstream,

00:36:33.610 --> 00:36:38.480
and it can pass through
the blood brain barrier.

00:36:38.480 --> 00:36:41.380
So it gets into our
central nervous system

00:36:41.380 --> 00:36:43.570
and can wreak havoc.

00:36:43.570 --> 00:36:46.270
It can also go
through the placenta.

00:36:46.270 --> 00:36:52.360
And the fetus is just in there.

00:36:52.360 --> 00:36:54.590
I mean, it's just developing.

00:36:54.590 --> 00:36:57.670
And once methyl
mercury gets in there

00:36:57.670 --> 00:37:03.230
you can have total decontrol
of the whole thing.

00:37:03.230 --> 00:37:06.390
Everything can fall
apart for that.

00:37:06.390 --> 00:37:09.380
So this is really bad stuff.

00:37:09.380 --> 00:37:12.200
Now what we're going
to be doing in this lab

00:37:12.200 --> 00:37:16.340
is actually we're going
to be detecting this

00:37:16.340 --> 00:37:21.650
and we're going to be using our
new DMA 80 atomic absorption

00:37:21.650 --> 00:37:23.420
spectrometer.

00:37:23.420 --> 00:37:29.100
And this spectrometer
operates under three things.

00:37:29.100 --> 00:37:31.310
There are three
things happening here.

00:37:34.590 --> 00:37:39.260
So we've got
thermal degradation.

00:37:46.650 --> 00:37:50.130
You've got amalgamation.

00:37:56.620 --> 00:38:01.900
And we've got atomic absorption.

00:38:06.980 --> 00:38:11.660
This spectrometer has two
detectors and three cells.

00:38:11.660 --> 00:38:12.920
It's called a tri cell.

00:38:18.850 --> 00:38:22.965
So on the nanogram scale
and the PPB scale--

00:38:26.130 --> 00:38:31.140
one of the cells will
detect from about 0.01

00:38:31.140 --> 00:38:41.250
to 10 nanograms, which
is like 0.1 to 100 PPB.

00:38:41.250 --> 00:38:47.850
The next cell will detect
between 10 and 20 nanograms,

00:38:47.850 --> 00:38:52.290
which is 100 to 200 PPB.

00:38:52.290 --> 00:38:57.490
And the third cell will
pick up the last range

00:38:57.490 --> 00:39:10.400
from 20 to 1,500 nanograms,
which is 200 to 15,000 PPB.

00:39:10.400 --> 00:39:13.190
The detection limit
of this machine

00:39:13.190 --> 00:39:16.250
is to the thousandths
of a nanogram.

00:39:16.250 --> 00:39:25.970
So detects text down
to 0.001 nanogram.

00:39:25.970 --> 00:39:28.820
Can actually-- you're talking
almost a part per trillion

00:39:28.820 --> 00:39:30.720
there with this machine.

00:39:30.720 --> 00:39:34.470
So it's really a
fantastic machine.

00:39:34.470 --> 00:39:37.545
So let's actually see
how this machine works.

00:39:41.380 --> 00:39:44.910
So this is a little
schematic of this machine.

00:39:44.910 --> 00:39:49.120
And I did this on ChemDraw.

00:39:49.120 --> 00:39:51.600
So ChemDraw is amazing.

00:39:51.600 --> 00:39:57.030
It is just-- you can do just
about anything with ChemDraw.

00:39:57.030 --> 00:39:59.880
So we've got a tank
of oxygen that you'll

00:39:59.880 --> 00:40:01.840
see it sitting in the lab.

00:40:01.840 --> 00:40:05.670
And then we have this
autosampler, which

00:40:05.670 --> 00:40:09.480
is a 40 position autosampler.

00:40:09.480 --> 00:40:14.010
And so we'll be massing
out our fish, putting it

00:40:14.010 --> 00:40:15.720
into the autosampler.

00:40:15.720 --> 00:40:18.720
And then this little
pneumatic arm comes out,

00:40:18.720 --> 00:40:21.690
grabs your sample out of
the autosampler, and inserts

00:40:21.690 --> 00:40:26.420
it into this drying
decomposition oven.

00:40:26.420 --> 00:40:28.340
And the drying
decomposition oven

00:40:28.340 --> 00:40:32.960
will heat the sample up to
about 650 degrees or so.

00:40:32.960 --> 00:40:35.730
And it combusts everything.

00:40:35.730 --> 00:40:38.720
And all of the combustion
products of your sample

00:40:38.720 --> 00:40:42.530
are carried by the
stream of oxygen gas

00:40:42.530 --> 00:40:46.010
into this catalyst tube furnace.

00:40:46.010 --> 00:40:48.650
Everything goes in
the catalyst tube.

00:40:48.650 --> 00:40:53.090
And that catalyst tube gets
heated up to about 500 degrees.

00:40:53.090 --> 00:40:55.760
And it pulls everything out--

00:40:55.760 --> 00:41:00.320
literally all the NOxes, SOxes,
everything you can think of.

00:41:00.320 --> 00:41:05.040
Not only that, it converts
every mercury species,

00:41:05.040 --> 00:41:10.380
including methyl mercury down
to the elemental mercury.

00:41:10.380 --> 00:41:13.890
The only thing that comes
out of that catalyst tube

00:41:13.890 --> 00:41:16.900
is the elemental mercury.

00:41:16.900 --> 00:41:19.000
I know it's hard
to believe that,

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:23.170
but everything else stays
in the catalyst tube.

00:41:23.170 --> 00:41:25.510
So the elemental
mercury comes out

00:41:25.510 --> 00:41:28.630
and goes into a
gold amalgamator.

00:41:28.630 --> 00:41:34.200
And all it is a glass tube
filled with tiny gold beads.

00:41:34.200 --> 00:41:36.990
And the mercury comes
out, goes in there,

00:41:36.990 --> 00:41:40.330
and sticks to those beads.

00:41:40.330 --> 00:41:45.370
Then this gold amalgamator is
flash heated up to 900 degrees.

00:41:45.370 --> 00:41:46.570
And bam!

00:41:46.570 --> 00:41:49.210
You release the mercury vapor.

00:41:49.210 --> 00:41:52.360
And the vapor goes into
the atomic absorption

00:41:52.360 --> 00:41:55.780
part of the instrument that
has our tri cells-- our three

00:41:55.780 --> 00:41:57.730
cells.

00:41:57.730 --> 00:42:00.880
So we've got two mercury lamps.

00:42:00.880 --> 00:42:02.860
They're shining light
on the samples--

00:42:02.860 --> 00:42:06.010
like 254 nanometers.

00:42:06.010 --> 00:42:08.890
And the light goes in,
shines on the sample,

00:42:08.890 --> 00:42:11.830
and then we record the height
of the peak in the absorbance

00:42:11.830 --> 00:42:13.270
that's going on.

00:42:13.270 --> 00:42:16.570
And we figure out
our concentrations

00:42:16.570 --> 00:42:18.625
of the mercury in our samples.

00:42:21.940 --> 00:42:23.725
So this is a great machine.

